{
  "text": "To study in vivo effects of disrupting the AID miR-155 target site, we immunized the transgenic mice intraperitoneally with nitrophenol conjugated to chicken gamma globulin (NP-CGG). The NP hapten induces a well-characterized immune response [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] in peripheral lymphoid germinal centers (GC), microenvironments where activated lymphocytes undergo Ig diversification. Eighteen to 21 days after immunization, we evaluated After completing the GC reaction, activated B lymphocytes exit into the periphery and differentiate into plasma or memory cells. These post-GC B lymphocytes have been shown to cease expression of AID [CITATION_4] . Accordingly, the AicdaGfp control mice did not express AID-GFP in B cells in the peripheral blood ( Figure 4B ). In contrast, a GFP + population of B cells was consistently detected in the blood of immunized Aicda-Gfp-Mut mice ( Figure 4B ). These appeared to be a heterogeneous population of B lymphocytes (B220 int-hi ), which were mostly IgG1 + but also included IgM + and IgD + nonswitched cells.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "316937",
